Infrastructure and toolkit for teaching financial data science

How using cloud based solutions and transform quantitative finance teaching and embed computation as a central tennent of the curiculla.

Barry Quinn https://quinference.com (Queens Management School)https://qub.ac.uk/mgt
2021-07-19

Introduction

Modern finance is fundamentally a quantitative discipline, with most financial researchers solving problems via empirical analysis. , with advancements in AI and machine learning embedded in the growth of financial technology. The rise of big and alternative data also is created new opportunities in financial sector, including risk management, portfolio construction, investment banking and insurance. Finance graduates, who are highly literate in computing, have a rare opportunity to balance the exponential growth of artificial intelligence(AI)/data science with ethics, bias, and privacy to create a trustworthy data-driven decision process (Mahdavi and Kazemi 2020).

Finance and computation has gone hand in hand for centuries, with quantitative finance taking its roots from Bachelier’s Theory of Speculation (Bachelier 1900). On the buy-side: portfolio management was transformed with the quantitative research of Harry Markowitz in the early 1950’s shows how a complex mean-variance portfolio optimisation problem could be approximated by his Critical Line algorithm. Computerised algorithm trading championed by Ed Thorp, John Simons in the 1960’s shows arbitrage opportunities, unseen by traditional hedge fund managers, could be exploited to consistently beat the market. On the sell-side, a game changing breakthrough in the 1970s was an options pricing model (Black and Scholes 1973; Merton 1973), targeting explosive growth in the options markets (Cesa 2017). Ironically, the BSM model main weaknesses, seen a growth in financial computing demands, as quantitative researchers use more realistic continuous-time pricing models which require computationally challenging partial differential equations (Reisinger and Wissmann 2018). This long history solving financial problems with computation and algorithms has seen a new rebirth in the emerging field of financial data science, as the tension between the underlying paradigm of financial machine learning and the research philosophy in financial economics is slowly fading (Lommers, Harzli, and Kim 2021).

Computing environment

To understand more about the computational foundations for students we borrow from the extant statistical education literature (Kaplan 2007; Çetinkaya-Rundel and Rundel 2018). Much like teaching statistics/data science quantitative finance has two interconnected goals. 1. Get students to do something interesting with data (and code) within the first ten minutes of the first class. 2. Get students to think about computation as an integral part of the quantitative finance curriculum. An common solution is to use computing labs to facilitate computation exercises. The downside is that instructors usually do not have administrative access and therefore struggle accomplish even the basic maintenance tasks. Furthermore, this usually leads to common environment for all courses, rather than specialised set-ups for more enhanced student computational needs. Finally, to achieve the second goal requires active engagement of computation for all contact time. We use a web browser-based solutions, RStudio’s Workbench, to provide a frictionless student experience in both lectures and lab sessions. Workbench is professional data science server software, where facilitates interoperable computational insight integrate R and Python leveraging support for Jupyter, VSCode, and RStudio’s integrated development enviroment (IDE) (“RStudio Workbench,” n.d.).
